snippet.title: Best laptops
snippet.description: CNET editors choose and review the best thin and light laptops, notebooks, and ultrabooks.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Flip 15
snippet.description: Sony's unique attempt at a big-screen hybrid looks great and is reasonably priced, but it works better as a laptop than a tablet.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Duo 13
snippet.description: The Sony Vaio Duo 13 is ambitious, but less universally useful than other Windows 8 laptop-tablet hybrids. There may not be a real need for a slider-style PC.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Fit 14
snippet.description: The Sony Vaio Fit 14 is an all-around excellent laptop for the money that will satisfy the basic demands of everyday use for many people and look good doing it.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Tap 11
snippet.description: Sony's thin, powerful Tap 11 tablet shows up the competition in terms of design. It's not ideal for everyone, but only a few tweaks away from being the runaway leader in this smallish category.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Fit 11A Flip PC
snippet.description: This hybrid can shift between laptop, tablet, or kiosk modes, and includes a copy of Photoshop Elements 12.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Pro 11
snippet.description: The superthin, superlight Sony Vaio Pro 11 is everything we expect from an excellent ultrabook.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Pro 13 Touch
snippet.description: For those who want an excellent ultraportable laptop with more than just the latest Intel processors, the Sony Vaio Pro 13 Touch is it.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio E17
snippet.description: If you want a reasonably priced desktop-replacement big-screen laptop, the Vaio E17 is worth a look. But itâ€™s not a good Windows 8 showcase machine, and it lacks any touch interface other than a small touch pad.

snippet.title: Sony Vaio Tap 21
snippet.description: There may be a lot of touch-screen tabletop Windows 8 tablet PCs, but the Vaio Tap 21 has the looks to compete.
